creation of the image also integrate the style and interfere with the meaning. Considering
that refering pre-existing styles would add specific connoted meanings to illustration,
we sought to verify if this phenomenon would be associated to visual language variables
appropriation of such style. Given the multiplicity of meanings that the term style can
assume, Roland Barthes?s concept for writing was adopted, understanding it as a set of
choices made by the illustrator regarding the methods, tools, visual language and signs
used, on which the forces of personal style and culture act on. The experiment simulated
an illustration design project for a children?s book with a definition of a writing that, in this
context, has the function of establishing parameters to maintain the coherence of visual
language among the book?s illustrations. The starting point was a text adapted from a popular
tale by Silvio Romero entitled O bicho parachó, which proposed an approach to style
adequacy in order to emphasize its relationship with Brazilian popular culture. Thus, developing
a visual language that referred to this idea was one of the metters of the project.
